<table width="100%" style="margin-top:10px">
<tr>
	<td>
		<h2>SPOJ Problem Set (classical)</h2>
				<h1>10596. Monkey and apples</h1>
		<h2>Problem code: MON2012</h2>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>

<p align="justify">
<p>Monkey Chris loves apples. That's why he has planted lots of apple trees. He does two types of operations on this trees.Second operation (described "2" x y in input(without quotes)) means that all apples on interval x+c y+c get ripe(edible).  First operation (described by "1" x y(without quotes) in input) means counting ripe apple trees on interval x+c y+c. C=0 in the beginning and becomes the answer of each query("1" operation). Input begins with M(1&lt;=M&lt;=10^5) the number of operations. Afterwards M lines each of them is an operation ("1" or "2"). 1&lt;=X+C; Y+C&lt;=10^9. <br />Input<br /><br />3<br /><br />2 5 8<br /><br />2 7 10<br /><br />1 1 10<br /><br />Output<br /><br />6<br /><br />Input explanation:<br /><br />3 queries. Apples gets ripe on intervals 5-8 and 7-10.<br /><br />There are totally 6 ripe apple-trees on interval 1-10 so answer to query is 6.</p>

